communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

3) Date range: Between March 1, 2022 to May 31, 2022.

Sincerely,

Stuart Martin

title: Eric Bernay

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Eric Bernay
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records mentioning, relating to, or generated as a result of investigation into Eric Bernay (aka Eric Bernstein) (1906 - February 11, 1968), owner of record company Keynote Recordings and Soviet intelligence contact. Proof of death is not required as his date of birth was over 100 years ago.

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies. This is also to include any responsive records held in offsite locations, such as the Alexandria Records Center. Please include both investigatory and non-investigatory records in your search. If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Sincerely,

Paul Galante

title: Clarence Adams (January 1, 1930 – 1999)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Clarence Adams (January 1, 1930 – 1999)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records mentioning, relating to, or generated as a result of investigation or inquiry into Clarence Adams (January 1, 1930 – 1999). Adams was a U.S. soldier captured during the Korean War. He refused to return home during prisoner exchanges at the end of the war, and instead moved to China. Adams made propaganda for the Chinese office of Radio Hanoi during the Vietnam War. He returned to the United States via Hong Kong on May 26, 1966, citing that he missed his mother. The House Un-American Activities Committee subpoenaed Adams upon his return but did not question him publicly.

Adams' death is widely-known and has been widely reported, privacy concerns under FOIA Exemptions 6 and 7 are voided, as are any concerns under the Privacy Act. You may find a report on his death here: https://archive.commercialappeal.com/entertainment/the-long-road-home-ep-398926176-323991861.html

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records of both HQ and all field offices for all relevant names, agencies, organizations, companies and events including but not limited to those cited in the previous paragraphs and/or links as well as a cross-reference with the Southern Poverty Law Center to include any information provided by the SPLC.
